In the days before the flood, people were eating and drinking. They were marrying. They were giving their daughters in marriage. They were doing all these things until the day Noah entered the ark.
They didn't know anything about what was going to happen until the floods came and took them all. This is what will happen when the son of man comes.
There were two men in the field. One was harvesting, and the other was resting.
Two women will be grinding with a hand mill. They will take one and leave the other.
"So be watchful! You do not know on what day your Lord will come.
You need to understand something. Let's assume the homeowner knew at what time of the night the thief would come. In that case, he would have stayed awake. And he wouldn't have let his house be robbed.
Therefore you also must be ready; for the Son of Man is coming at an hour you do not expect.
Let's assume that a master appointed one of his servants in charge of the other servants in his house. The servant's task is to give them their food at the proper time. The master wants a faithful and wise servant for this purpose.
If the master returns and finds his servant doing his job, it will be good for the servant.
What I'm about to tell you is true. The master will give this servant responsibility over everything he has.
But let's suppose that servant is evil. Let's suppose he says to himself, 'My master will be away for a long time.'
Suppose he started beating other servants. And suppose he eats and drinks with those who drink a lot.
The master of this servant will return on a day when the servant does not expect him. He will return at a time when the servant does not know.
And then they will cut the man into pieces. They will send him to the place where liars go. And there people will cry and gnash their teeth.
"The Tale of Ten Maids of Honor"
"How will the kingdom of heaven be at that time? The ten virgins took their lamps and went out to meet the bridegroom.
Five of them were fools. Five of them were wise.
Fools took their lanterns with them, but they didn't take olive oil.
The wise took the oil in jars with their lamps.
The groom didn't come for a long time. That's why the women who were helping the bride got tired and fell asleep.
In the middle of the night, someone shouted: "Here comes the bridegroom! Go out to meet him!
Then all the bride's maids awoke and trimmed their lamps.
The fools said to the wise, "Give us some of your oil, for our lamps are about to go out."
"No," they answered. "There may not be enough for us all. Go instead to those who sell oil. Buy some for yourselves."
"They went to buy oil. But on their way, the groom arrived. The women who were present went in with him to the wedding dinner. And the door was closed."
Then the other bridesmaids also came. And they said, "Sir! Sir! Open the door for us!"
But he answered, "What I am about to tell you is true. I do not know you."
"Therefore be alert, for you do not know the day or the hour when the bridegroom will come. The parable of the three servants"
"Again, the kingdom of heaven is like a man who was going on a journey, who called his servants and entrusted his property to them.
He gave $10,000 to one. He gave $4,000 to another. He gave $2,000 to the third. The man gave each servant the amount he knew the servant could handle. Then he continued on his journey.
The servant who received $10,000 immediately went and invested his money. He made an additional $10,000.
He who gets $4000, gets $4000 more.
But the man who received two thousand dollars went and dug a hole in the ground, hid his master's money in it, and then buried it.
After a long time, the master of those servants returned. He wanted to collect all the money they had earned.
The man who was given $10,000 brought another $10,000. He said, "Sir, you trusted me and gave me $10,000. Look, I've made another $10,000."
His master answered, "Well done, good and faithful servant! You have been faithful over a little; I will set you over much. Enter into the joy of your master!"
"Come on, even the man who had $4000. He said, 'Sir, you have become my trusted one and gave me $4000. Look, I made another $4000.'"
His master answered, "Well done, good and faithful servant! You have been faithful over a little; I will set you over much. Enter into the joy of your master!"
Then came the man who had received two thousand dollars. He said, "Sir, I knew you to be a hard man, reaping where you did not sow and gathering where you did not scatter seed.
And so I was afraid. I went out and buried your $2000 in the ground. Look, this is what comes back to you.
His master answered, "You wicked and lazy servant! Did you know that I harvest where I did not sow? Did you know that I gather crops where I did not scatter seed?
So, you should have put my money in the bank. And when I returned, I would have gotten it back with interest.
Then his master said to the other servants, 'Take the thousand dollars from him and give it to the one who has twenty thousand.'
Anyone who has something will take more. They will have more than they need. What about those who have nothing? Even what they have will be taken from them.
They drove that useless servant out into the darkness, where people will weep and gnash their teeth. Sheep and goats.
"The Son of Man came with all his glory, and all the angels were with him. And he will sit on his throne of glory in heaven."
All nations will be gathered before Him. And the people will be separated into two groups, like a shepherd who separates the sheep from the goats.
He will drive the sheep to his right and the goats to his left.
Then the King will say to those on his right, 'Come, you who are blessed by my Father, inherit the kingdom prepared for you from the creation of the world.
I was hungry, and you gave me something to eat. I was thirsty, and you gave me something to drink. I was a stranger, and you welcomed me.
I needed clothes. You gave them to me. I was sick. You took care of me. I was in prison. You came to visit me.
Then those who did good deeds will answer, saying: "Our Lord, when did we see You hungry and feed You? Or thirsty and give You drink?"
When did we see you a stranger and bring you in? When did we see you in need of things and give them to you?
"When have we seen you sick or in prison and not gone to visit you?"
The king will answer: 'What I am about to tell you is true. Whatever you have done for one of my least important brothers, you have done for me.'
"Then he will say to those on his left, 'Depart from me, you cursed, into the eternal fire prepared for the devil and his angels.
I was hungry. But you didn't give me anything to eat. I was thirsty. But you didn't give me anything to drink.
I was a stranger, and you did not welcome me. I was in need of clothes, and you did not give me any. I was sick and in prison, but you did not take care of me.
And they also will answer and say, 'Lord, when did we see you hungry or thirsty, and did not help you? When did we see you a stranger, or needing clothes, or sick, or in prison, and did not help you?'
He will say: "This is what I will tell you is true. Everything you have not done for one of these who have no value, you have not done it for me."
"Then they will go away to eternal punishment, but those who have done good will receive eternal life."
The plan to kill Jesus
When Jesus had finished saying all these things, he said to his disciples,
As you know, Easter is in two days. The Son of Man will be handed over to be crucified.
Then the chief priests and the elders of the people assembled in the palace of the high priest, Caiaphas.
They plotted to arrest Jesus in a clever way. They wanted to kill him.
"But not during the feast," they said. "It might stir up trouble." A woman poured perfume on Jesus.
Jesus was in the house of Simon the leper at Bethany.
A woman came to Jesus, carrying a beautifully sealed flask filled with very expensive perfume. She poured the perfume over his head as he sat at the table.
When the disciples saw this, they were indignant. They said, "Why this waste?"
The perfume could have been sold at a high price. The money could have been given to the poor.
Jesus was aware of this. He said to them, "Why are you bothering this woman? She has done a good thing for me."
You will always have kind people with you. But I will not always be with you.
She sprayed perfume on my body to prepare me for burial.
What I am about to tell you is true. What was done will be repeated wherever this good news spreads throughout the world. It will be repeated so that it is remembered. Judas agreed to hand over Jesus.
One of the twelve went to the chief priests. His name was Judas Iscariot.
And he asked them, "What will you give me, and I will deliver Jesus to you?" And they paid him thirty pieces of silver.
And from that time Judas sought opportunity to betray him unto them. The Last Supper
It was the first day of the Festival of Unleavened Bread. The disciples came to Jesus and asked, "Where do you want us to make preparations for you to eat the Passover?"
He replied, "Go into the city to a certain man and tell him, 'The Teacher says: My time is near. I will keep the Passover at your house with my disciples.'"
And so the disciples did as Jesus had directed them; they prepared the Passover meal.
And when evening came, Jesus was reclining at the table with the twelve.
As they were eating, he said, "Truly I tell you, one of you will betray me."
The disciples were very sorrowful. They began to say to him, one by one, "Is it I, Lord?"
Jesus answered, "He who dips his hand with me in the dish, he will betray me."
"Nevertheless, the Son of Man will go just as it is written about him. Woe to that man who betrays the Son of Man! It would have been better for him if he had not been born."
It was Judas who betrayed him. He said, "I am not the one, am I, Teacher?" Jesus answered, "Yes, it is you."
And as they were eating, Jesus took bread, gave thanks, broke it, and gave it to his disciples, saying, "Take, eat; this is my body."
Then he took the cup, praised Allah, and passed it to them, saying, "Drink from it, all of you."
This is my blood of the covenant, which is poured out for many for the forgiveness of sins.
This is what I tell you: From now on, I will not drink wine with you until the day I drink it with you in my Father's kingdom.
Then they sang a hymn and went out to the Mount of Olives. Jesus said Peter would fail.
Jesus said to them, "You will all fall away because of me this night. For it is written, 'I will strike the shepherd, and the sheep will be scattered.' (Zechariah 13:7)
But after I am raised from the dead, I will go ahead of you into Galilee.
Peter answered, "Everyone may forsake you, but I will never do so."
Jesus answered, "Verily I say unto thee, Before the cock crow, thou shalt deny me thrice."
But Peter said, "I may have to die with you, but I will never say that I don't know you." All the other disciples said the same. Jesus' prayer in Gethsemane
And Jesus went with his disciples to a place called Gethsemane, and he said to them, "Sit here until I go over there and pray."
And he took with him Peter and the two sons of Zebedee. And he began to be sorrowful and very troubled.
Then he said to them, "My soul is very sorrowful, even to the point of death. Stay here and keep watch with me."
He walked a little further. Then he fell face first to the ground. He prayed and said, "Father, if possible, let this cup of suffering pass from me. Yet, let your will be done, not mine."
Then he returned to his disciples, whom he found sleeping. And he said to Peter, "Could you not watch with me for one hour?"
"Watch and pray. That's how you won't fall into sin when you're tempted. The spirit is willing, but the flesh is weak."
Jesus walked away again. He prayed, saying, "Father, if it is possible, let this cup pass from me. But if I must drink it, may your will be done."
He returned later. He found them sleeping again. They couldn't keep their eyes open.
So he left them and went away again. And a third time he prayed the same prayer.
Then he came back to the disciples and said to them, "Are you still sleeping and resting? Behold, the hour is at hand, and the Son of Man is being delivered into the hands of sinners."
"Get up! Let's go! Here comes the one who will hand me over to them!" Jesus was arrested.
And while Jesus was still speaking, Judas arrived, one of the Twelve. A large crowd was with him, carrying swords and clubs, sent by the chief priests and the elders of the people.
Judas, who had resolved to betray Jesus, had given them a signal: "The man I shall kiss is the one; seize him."
So Judas went to Jesus immediately and said, "Hail, Rabbi!" and kissed him.
Jesus answered, "Friend, do what you have come to do." Then the men stepped forward, seized Jesus, and arrested him.
At that moment, one of Jesus' companions reached for his sword, drew it, and struck the high priest's servant, cutting off his ear.
And Jesus said to him, "Put your sword back in its place. For all who take the sword will perish by the sword."
"Do you think I can't ask for help from Dad? He'll send an army of over 70,000 angels right away."
But how will the prophecies mentioned in the sacred books be fulfilled then? They say that this must happen in this way.
At that time Jesus spoke to the crowd. He said, "Did I come out against you with a band of armed men?" And he asked them, "Was it necessary for you to come out with swords and clubs to arrest me? I sat daily in the temple teaching, and you did not arrest me."
But all this has happened so that the prophecies of the prophets might be fulfilled." Then all the disciples left him and fled. Jesus before the Sanhedrin
And those who had arrested Jesus led him to Caiaphas, the high priest, where the teachers of the law and the elders had assembled.
Peter followed Jesus at a distance, not far away. He went directly to the high priest's courtyard. He entered and sat with the guards to see what would happen.
The chief priests and all the members of the Sanhedrin were looking for evidence they could use against Jesus. They wanted to kill him.
But they found no evidence, even though many false witnesses came forward to testify. Finally, two other witnesses came forward to give their testimony.
They said: "This man said: 'I can destroy the temple of God and rebuild it in three days.'"
And then the high priest stood up. He addressed Jesus: "Will you not answer? What are these charges that these men are bringing against you?"
But Jesus remained silent. The high priest said to him, "I adjure you by the living God, tell us if you are the Christ, the Son of God."
"Yes, it is as you say," Jesus answered. "But I tell you all: In the coming days, you will see the Son of Man sitting at the right hand of the Mighty One. You will see the Son of Man coming on the clouds of heaven."
And after that, the high priest tore his clothes and said, "He has spoken blasphemy! Why do we need other witnesses? You heard him say these evil words."
"What are you saying?" "He needs to die!" he replied.
Then they spat in his face. They struck him with their fists. Others slapped him.
They said, "Prophesy to us, Christ, who hit you?" Peter said he did not know Jesus.
Peter was sitting in the courtyard. A servant girl came to him and said, "You also were with Jesus the Galilean."
But before them all, Peter said that he was not. "I do not know what you are talking about," he said.
Then he went out to the gate leading to the courtyard. And there another woman saw him and said to the people, "This man was with Jesus of Nazareth."
He said again that it wasn't so. And he swore, saying, "I do not know this man!"
A little later, those who stood there approached Peter and said, "Surely you are one of them; your accent gives you away."
And immediately Peter began to curse and swear, saying, "I do not know this man." And the rooster crowed.
Peter remembered what Jesus had said to him: "Before the cock crows, you will deny me three times and say that you do not know me." And Peter went out and wept bitterly.
Judas hangs himself.
It was early morning. All the chief priests and elders of the people decided to kill Jesus.
They bound him and led him away. Then they handed him over to Pilate, the governor.
Judas, who had betrayed Jesus, saw that they had sentenced Him to death. He felt ashamed and deeply regretted his actions. So, he returned the thirty pieces of silver to the chief priests and elders.
"I have sinned," he said. "I have delivered an innocent man." "What's it to us?" they replied. "That's your problem."
And so, Judas threw the money into the temple and left. Then he went and hanged himself.
The chief priests collected the money. They said, "It is not lawful to put this money into the treasury, for this is blood money, the price of a man's life."
So they decided to use the money to buy a piece of land to bury the pottery. People from other countries would be buried there.
And that is why it is still called the Field of Blood to this day.
And so were fulfilled the words that the prophet Jeremiah had spoken: "They gave me thirty pieces of silver, the price that the sons of Israel had set for him."
"They paid the equivalent of thirty pieces of silver for the potter's field, as the Lord commanded me" (Zechariah 11:12, 13; Jeremiah 19:1-13; 32:6-9). They brought Jesus to Pilate.
Jesus stood before the governor, and the governor asked him, "Are you the King of the Jews?" Jesus answered, "You have said so."
But when the chief priests and elders accused him, he did not answer.
And then Pilate said: Don't you hear the charges they are making against you?
But Jesus made no answer, not even to a single charge. The governor was greatly amazed.
It was the governor's custom at Easter to release one prisoner. The people could choose whoever they wanted.
At that time they had a well-known prisoner named Barabbas.
So when the crowd had gathered, Pilate asked them, "Whom do you want me to release for you? Barabbas or Jesus who is called the Messiah?"
Pilate knew that the chief priests were jealous. He knew that was why they had handed Jesus over to him.
Now while Pilate was sitting on the judge's bench, his wife sent him a message: "Have nothing to do with that innocent man, for today I have suffered a great deal in a dream because of him."
But the chief priests and the elders persuaded the crowd to ask for Barabbas and to have Jesus put to death.
"Which of the two men do you want me to release?" asked the governor. "Barabbas," they answered.
"What, then, shall I do with Jesus who is called the Christ?" asked Pilate. And they all answered, "Crucify him!"
"Why? What crime has he committed?" asked Pilate. But they shouted all the louder, "Crucify him!"
Pilate saw that he was getting nowhere with them, and that they were becoming agitated. So he took water and washed his hands in front of them, saying, "I am innocent of this man's blood; see to it yourselves."
All the people answered: "I and my children will bear the responsibility for his death!"
Pilate released Barabbas, but ordered Jesus to be flogged and then handed him over to be crucified. The soldiers mocked Jesus.
The governor's soldiers took Jesus into the palace, which was called the Praetorium. And the whole company of soldiers gathered around him.
They stripped him and dressed him in a purple robe.
And after that they took up thorns and made a crown of them, and put it on his head. And they put a reed in his right hand. And they bowed the knee before him, and mocked him, saying, "Hail, King of the Jews!"
They spat on him. They hit him on the head with a stick repeatedly.
After they mocked him, they took away his robe. They dressed him in his own clothes. Then they led him away to crucify him. They crucified Jesus on the cross.
And when they had gone out of the city, they found a man of Cyrene named Simon, and they compelled him to carry the cross.
And they came to a place called Golgotha. And the word Golgotha means "place of the skull."
And there they mixed wine with bitter herbs and offered it to Jesus to drink. But when he tasted it, he refused to drink it.
And when they had crucified him, they divided his garments among them by casting lots.
They sat there and kept watching him.
They put a sign over his head that read, "This is Jesus, the King of the Jews."
Two robbers were crucified with him, one on his right and the other on his left.
The people who passed by him started talking about Jesus and laughing at him. They shook their heads.
And they said, "Are you the one who is going to destroy the temple and rebuild it in three days? Save yourself! If you are the Son of God, come down from the cross!"
The chief priests, the teachers of the law and the elders mocked him also.
And they said, "He saved others, but he cannot save himself! He is the King of Israel! Let him come down from the cross now, and we will believe in him.
He believes in God. Let God save him now if he wants him. It is he who said, "I am the Son of God."
In the same way, the robbers who were crucified with Jesus also mocked him. The death of Jesus.
From noon until three o'clock, the whole earth was covered in darkness.
Jesus cried out in a loud voice around the ninth hour, saying, "Eli, Eli, lema sabachthani?" which means, "My God, my God, why have you forsaken me?" (Psalm 22:1)
And some of the bystanders, hearing Jesus cry out, said, "He is calling Elijah."
So one of them ran and took a sponge, filled it with sour wine, put it on a reed, and offered it to Jesus to drink.
The others said, "Leave him alone. Let's see if Elijah will come to save him."
After Jesus cried out loudly again, he died.
At that moment, the curtain of the temple was torn in two, from top to bottom. The earth shook, and the rocks were split.
The tombs were opened. And many bodies of the saints who had fallen asleep were raised, and they came out of the tombs and entered the holy city.
They came out of the tombs. After Jesus had risen from the dead, they went into the holy city. There they appeared to a great many people.
The Roman commander and the guards who were watching over Jesus saw the earthquake and everything that had happened. They were terrified and said, "This man was definitely the Son of God!"
A large number of women were watching from a distance. They had followed Jesus from Galilee to take care of his needs.
Mary Magdalene was among them. There was also Mary, the mother of James and Joseph, and the mother of the sons of Zebedee. They buried Jesus.
And when the even was come, there came a rich man of Arimathaea, named Joseph, who also himself had been Jesus' disciple.
He went to Pilate and asked for Jesus' body. And Pilate ordered that it be given to him.
Joseph took the body and wrapped it in a clean linen cloth.
And he laid it in his new tomb which he had hewn out of the rock. And he rolled a great stone to the door of the tomb. Then he went away.
Mary Magdalene and the other Mary were sitting there opposite the tomb. The guards at the tomb.
The next day was the day after the Preparation. And the chief priests and the Pharisees went to Pilate.
"Sir," they said, "we remember something that liar said while he was still alive. He claimed, 'In three days I will rise again.'"
So give the order to secure the tomb until the third day, otherwise his disciples may come and steal the body, and then tell people that Jesus has risen from the dead, and this last lie will be worse than the first.
Pilate answered, "Take a guard. Go, make the tomb as secure as you can."
So they went and made the tomb secure, sealing the stone and setting the guard.
Jesus rises from the dead.
Now when the Sabbath was over, Mary Magdalene and Mary the other went to see the tomb.
There was a strong earthquake. An angel of the Lord came down from heaven. The angel went to the tomb. He rolled away the stone and sat on it.
His body shone like lightning. His clothes were white as snow.
The guards were so frightened of him that they trembled and became like the dead.
The angel said to the women, "Do not be afraid, for I know that you are looking for Jesus who was crucified."
He's not here! He left just as he said he would! Come and see the spot where he was sleeping.
Go quickly and tell his disciples, 'He has risen from the dead and is going ahead of you to Galilee. There you will see him.' That is my message for you.
So the women hurried away from the tomb, afraid yet filled with joy, and ran to tell his disciples.
And suddenly Jesus appeared to them and said, "Peace be with you!" Then they came to him, took hold of his feet, and worshiped him.
Then Jesus said to them, "Do not be afraid. Go and tell my brothers to go to Galilee, and there they will see me." The guards reported this to the chief priests.
And as the women were going, behold, some of the guard came into the city and told the chief priests all that had happened.
When the high priests met with the elders, they made a plan. They gave the soldiers a large sum of money.
They said to the soldiers, "We want you to say, 'His disciples came at night and stole his body while we were sleeping.'"
If the governor hears about this report, we'll pay him a bribe. That will keep you out of trouble.
So the soldiers took the money and did as they were told. This story has been spread among the Jews to this day. These were the last instructions Jesus gave to his disciples.
And after that, the disciples went to Galilee. They went to the mountain where Jesus had told them to go.
When they saw him, they prostrated before him, but some of them were doubtful.
Then Jesus came to them and said, "All authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me."
Therefore go and make disciples of all nations, baptizing them in the name of the Father and of the Son and of the Holy Spirit.
"Teach them to obey everything I have commanded you. And know that I am with you always, to the end of the age."
John the Baptist prepares the way.
This is the beginning of the good news about Jesus Christ, the Son of God.
Long ago, the prophet Isaiah wrote: "I will send my messenger ahead of you, who will prepare your way." (Malachi 3:1)
"A voice cries out in the wilderness: 'Prepare the way for the Lord, make straight his paths'" (Isaiah 40:3).
And so John came. He was baptizing people in the desert. He also preached to the people that they should be baptized and repent of their sins. Then God would forgive them.
All the people of the Judean countryside and all the people of Jerusalem went out to him. When they acknowledged their sins, John baptized them in the Jordan River.
John wore clothes made of camel hair. He had a leather belt around his waist. He ate locusts and wild honey.
This is what John the Baptist proclaimed: "After me comes one who is mightier than I, and I am not worthy to stoop down and untie the thong of his sandals.
"I baptize you with water, but he will baptize you with the Holy Spirit." - The Baptism and Temptation of Jesus
At that time Jesus came from Nazareth in Galilee and was baptized by John in the Jordan River.
Jesus came up out of the water. At that moment, he saw the heavens torn open and the Spirit descending on him like a dove.
He heard a voice from the sky. It said to him, "You are my son, and I love you. I am very pleased with you."
And immediately the Spirit drove Jesus into the wilderness.
He was in the desert for 40 days, and the devil tested him. Wild animals did not hurt Jesus, and angels took care of him. Jesus chooses the first disciples.
After John was arrested, Jesus went to Galilee. He began preaching the good news from God.
He said, "The time is fulfilled, and the kingdom of God is at hand. Repent, and believe the gospel!"
One day Jesus was walking by the Sea of Galilee. There he saw Simon and his brother Andrew. They were casting a net into the lake; they were fishermen.
Jesus said, "Come. Follow me, and I will make you fishers of men."
So they left their nets at once and followed him.
Then Jesus walked a little further. As he walked, he saw James the son of Zebedee and his brother John. They were in a boat mending their nets.
So they left their father Zebedee in the boat with the hired men, and went off to follow Jesus. And Jesus drove out a demon that was mute.
Jesus and his companions went to Capernaum. And when the Sabbath came, he entered the synagogue and began to teach.
The people were amazed at his teaching. He taught them as one having authority, not as the scribes.
Then a man in their synagogue who had an unclean spirit cried out, "What do you want with us, Jesus of Nazareth? Have you come to destroy us? I know who you are—the Holy One of God!"
"What do you want from us, Jesus of Nazareth? Have you come to destroy us? I know who you are. You are the Holy One of God!"
"Be silent!" Jesus said sternly. "Come out of him!"
The evil spirit shook the man violently. Then it came out of him with a shout.
All the people were amazed, and they said to each other, "What is this? A new teaching with authority! He even commands evil spirits and they obey him."
The news about Jesus spread quickly throughout Galilee. Jesus healed many people.
Jesus and those with him left the synagogue and went immediately with James and John to the house of Simon and Andrew.
Simon's mother-in-law was lying in bed with a fever. They told Jesus about her.
So he went to her, took her hand, and helped her up. The fever left her. Then she began to serve them.
That evening, after sunset, the people brought to Jesus all who were sick and those who were demon-possessed.
All the city's inhabitants gathered at the gate.
Jesus healed many of them. They were suffering from all kinds of diseases. He also cast out many demons. But he would not allow the demons to speak, because they knew who he was. Jesus prayed in a solitary place.
It was still very early in the morning, and darkness had not yet lifted. Jesus got up and left the house. He went to a place where he could be alone. And there he prayed.
Simon and his friends went to look for Jesus.
When they found him, they shouted: "Everyone is looking for you!"
Jesus answered, "Let us go somewhere else—to the nearby towns. I must preach there also. That is why I have come."
So he traveled throughout all of Galilee, teaching in their synagogues and casting out demons. Healing of a Man with Leprosy by Jesus
A man with a skin disease came to Jesus, knelt down on his knees, and begged him, saying, "If you want to, you can make me clean."
Jesus was filled with deep concern. He reached out his hand and touched the man. He said, "I am willing to do this." "Be 'clean'!"
The disease left him immediately. He has recovered.
Jesus sent him away immediately. He gave the man a severe warning.
He said, "Do not tell anyone about this. Go and show yourself to the priest. Offer the sacrifices that Moses commanded. This will be evidence for the priest and the people that you are 'clean'."
But the man went out and began to proclaim it freely and to spread the news, so that Jesus could no longer enter a town openly. He remained outside in secluded places, but people from all quarters continued to gather around him.
Jesus heals a man who was unable to walk.
After a few days, Jesus returned to Capernaum. And the people heard that He had come back to the house.
A large crowd gathered, so large that there was no more room. There was not even room outside the door. And Jesus preached the word to them.
Four of those who came were carrying a man who could not walk.
